tra and the desire that so and so team and its quarterback should do well a=
nd win was still present in the mind as a background thought. Except for th=
at thought and the sound of the mantra, there was pretty much no other thou=
ght in the mind.
 
Suddenly, a thought arose in his mind (from where?): "en=
ough now - the job is done". That thought disturbed the focus and his shakt=
i came down. He was then aware of his body and was aware of his physical su=
rroundings. He opened his eyes and looked at the TV. Some 40-45 seconds wer=
e left in the clock. There was a touchdown within a few seconds and the oth=
er small team went ahead. The game was over.
 
In matters like this, cause =
and effect analysis is very difficult and not worth it. This sadhaka may or=
 may not have *caused* anything. But, what he experienced when his shakti r=
ose and the mind was focused is quite interesting and different from what h=
e would normally experience in such a situation. A communion between onesel=
f, a mantra and a sankalpa was achieved and it was a strange experience. Th=
e way the awareness arose that "the job is done" and the way touchdown happ=
ened a few seconds later was interesting.
 
